# UI Components & Library Adapters

## 1. Always Use shadcn/ui for UI

This project uses [shadcn/ui](https://ui.shadcn.com) (`base-nova` style, `lucide` icons, Tailwind CSS v4). All UI components must come from shadcn/ui or be built on top of it.

### Rules

- **Use shadcn/ui components first.** Before building a custom component, check if shadcn/ui has one: Button, Input, Select, Dialog, Sheet, Table, Card, Form, etc.
- **Install via CLI**: `bunx shadcn@latest add <component>` — installs to `packages/ui/src/components/`
- **Import from `@workspace/ui`**: Never install shadcn components directly in `apps/web`. Always install in `packages/ui/` and import via the alias.

```tsx
// GOOD
import { Button } from '@workspace/ui/components/button'
import { Input } from '@workspace/ui/components/input'
import { cn } from '@workspace/ui/lib/utils'

// BAD — never import raw Radix/Base UI primitives directly in app code
import { Button } from '@base-ui/react/button'
import * as Dialog from '@radix-ui/react-dialog'
```

- **Never use native HTML form controls when shadcn/ui equivalents exist.** In particular, never use `<select>` / `<option>` — always use the shadcn `Select` family. The same applies to `<input type="checkbox">` (use `Checkbox`), `<input type="radio">` (use `RadioGroup`), etc.

```tsx
// BAD — native <select>
<select value={value} onChange={(e) => setValue(e.target.value)}>
  <option value="">Choose…</option>
  <option value="a">A</option>
</select>

// GOOD — shadcn Select (Base UI)
// IMPORTANT: pass `items` to Select.Root so the trigger shows the label, not the raw value.
// Base UI's Select.Value renders the raw value by default; `items` maps value→label.
import {
  Select, SelectContent, SelectItem, SelectTrigger, SelectValue,
} from '@workspace/ui/components/select'

const items = [
  { value: 'a', label: 'Option A' },
  { value: 'b', label: 'Option B' },
]

<Select value={value} onValueChange={setValue} items={items}>
  <SelectTrigger className="w-full">
    <SelectValue placeholder="Choose…" />
  </SelectTrigger>
  <SelectContent>
    <SelectItem value="a">Option A</SelectItem>
    <SelectItem value="b">Option B</SelectItem>
  </SelectContent>
</Select>
```

- **Use `cn()` for class merging**: Always use `cn()` from `@workspace/ui/lib/utils` — never raw `clsx` or string concatenation.
- **Use `lucide-react` for icons**: The project standard. Import individual icons directly.

```tsx
// GOOD
import { Check } from 'lucide-react'

// BAD — don't mix icon libraries
import { FaCheck } from 'react-icons/fa'
```

- **Extend shadcn components, don't replace them**: If you need a variant that doesn't exist, add it to the component's `cva` variants in `packages/ui/`. Don't create a parallel component.

### Where Components Live

| Location | What goes there |
|---|---|
| `packages/ui/src/components/` | Shared, reusable shadcn/ui components (no business logic) |
| `apps/web/components/` | App-specific components that combine shared UI with business logic |

## 2. Adapter Pattern for External Libraries

**Every external utility library must be wrapped in an adapter module.** Never import external libs directly in app code. This enables swapping implementations (e.g. `date-fns` to `dayjs`, `axios` to `ky`) by changing a single file.

### Adapter Location

All adapters live in a shared package. As the project grows, create `packages/utils/` with subpath exports. For now, place adapters in `packages/ui/src/lib/` or `apps/web/lib/`.

```
packages/
└── ui/
    └── src/
        └── lib/
            ├── utils.ts          # cn() — already exists
            ├── date.ts           # Date adapter
            ├── currency.ts       # Currency/number formatting adapter
            └── http.ts           # HTTP client adapter (if needed)
```

### Date Adapter Example

```typescript
// packages/ui/src/lib/date.ts (or packages/utils/src/date.ts)
import { format, formatDistanceToNow, parseISO, isAfter, isBefore, addDays, subDays } from 'date-fns'

export function formatDate(date: string | Date, pattern = 'PPP'): string {
  const d = typeof date === 'string' ? parseISO(date) : date
  return format(d, pattern)
}

export function formatRelativeTime(date: string | Date): string {
  const d = typeof date === 'string' ? parseISO(date) : date
  return formatDistanceToNow(d, { addSuffix: true })
}

export function formatShortDate(date: string | Date): string {
  return formatDate(date, 'MMM d, yyyy')
}

export function formatDateTime(date: string | Date): string {
  return formatDate(date, 'PPP p')
}

export function isDateAfter(date: Date, comparison: Date): boolean {
  return isAfter(date, comparison)
}

export function isDateBefore(date: Date, comparison: Date): boolean {
  return isBefore(date, comparison)
}

export { addDays, subDays, parseISO }
```

```tsx
// GOOD — app code imports from adapter
import { formatDate, formatRelativeTime } from '@workspace/ui/lib/date'

function PostDate({ date }: { date: string }) {
  return <time>{formatDate(date)}</time>
}

// BAD — never import date-fns directly in components
import { format } from 'date-fns'
```

### Currency / Number Formatting Adapter

```typescript
// packages/ui/src/lib/currency.ts
const defaultLocale = 'en-US'

export function formatCurrency(amount: number, currency = 'USD', locale = defaultLocale): string {
  return new Intl.NumberFormat(locale, {
    style: 'currency',
    currency,
  }).format(amount)
}

export function formatNumber(value: number, locale = defaultLocale): string {
  return new Intl.NumberFormat(locale).format(value)
}

export function formatPercentage(value: number, locale = defaultLocale): string {
  return new Intl.NumberFormat(locale, {
    style: 'percent',
    minimumFractionDigits: 1,
  }).format(value)
}
```

### HTTP client adapter (optional)

Use a small `lib/http.ts` (or similar) **only** when you have many generic JSON calls to arbitrary backends and want one place to swap `fetch` for another client.

**Do not** add an app-only wrapper whose sole job is proxying Better Auth — that duplicates the official integration for no gain.

### Better Auth + Next.js

Server config lives in `packages/auth`; the app exposes the handler at `apps/web/app/api/auth/[...all]/route.ts`.

**Preferred in this repo:** a single **`apps/web/lib/auth-client.ts`** built with **`createAuthClient`** from **`better-auth/client`** (or `better-auth/react` if you need `useSession` / hooks). Use **`authClient.signIn.email`**, **`signUp.email`**, **`signOut`**, **`requestPasswordReset`**, **`resetPassword`**, etc. — not ad-hoc `fetch` to `/api/auth/...`.

- Align **`baseURL`** with **`BETTER_AUTH_URL`** via **`NEXT_PUBLIC_BETTER_AUTH_URL`** (see `.env.example`).
- Use **absolute** `callbackURL` / `redirectTo` (include origin), per [email & password best practices](https://www.better-auth.com/docs/authentication/email-password).
- Docs: [Next.js](https://www.better-auth.com/docs/integrations/nextjs) · [Basic usage (client)](https://www.better-auth.com/docs/basic-usage) · [LLMs.txt](https://better-auth.com/llms.txt)

Do **not** add a redundant `lib/auth-http` that only re-wraps `fetch`. Better Auth is the HTTP abstraction.

### Slug / String Utility Adapter

```typescript
// packages/ui/src/lib/slug.ts
import slugify from '@sindresorhus/slugify'

export function toSlug(text: string): string {
  return slugify(text)
}

export function toTitleCase(text: string): string {
  return text.replace(/\b\w/g, (char) => char.toUpperCase())
}
```

## 3. How to Apply This Pattern

### When adding a new external library:

1. **Install the package** in the correct workspace (`packages/ui` for shared, `apps/web` for app-specific)
2. **Create an adapter** in `lib/` that wraps the library's API with your own function names
3. **Export only what consumers need** — don't re-export the entire library
4. **Import the adapter** in app code, never the raw library

### When an adapter already exists:

- Add new functions to the existing adapter
- Keep the same naming conventions
- Don't create a second adapter for the same domain

### The rule of thumb:

> If `import { X } from 'some-external-lib'` appears in a file under `apps/` or `packages/ui/src/components/`, it's wrong. It should be `import { X } from '@workspace/ui/lib/adapter'` or `import { X } from '@/lib/adapter'`.

**Exception:** Use **`@/lib/auth-client`** (`createAuthClient` from **`better-auth/client`** or **`better-auth/react`**) for all Better Auth actions from the browser. Raw `fetch` to `/api/auth/*` is only for rare cases not exposed on the client API.

### Exceptions

These libraries are fine to import directly (they ARE the standard interface):
- `react`, `react-dom`, `next/*` (framework)
- `drizzle-orm/*` (already wrapped in `packages/db`)
- `better-auth/*` (server: `packages/auth`; client: optional `better-auth/client` — see Better Auth + Next.js above)
- `zod` (validation — universal, no alternative needed)
- `tailwind-merge`, `clsx`, `class-variance-authority` (CSS utilities used only inside `packages/ui`)
- `lucide-react` (icon library — standard for the project)
- **`@/lib/auth-client`** — single `createAuthClient` instance for sign-in, sign-up, sign-out, password reset, etc.

## 4. Checklist for Code Review

- [ ] UI built with shadcn/ui components, not raw HTML or third-party UI kits
- [ ] No native `<select>`, `<input type="checkbox">`, or `<input type="radio">` — use shadcn `Select`, `Checkbox`, `RadioGroup`
- [ ] Every `<Select>` has an `items` prop mapping `value→label` (Base UI renders raw `value` in the trigger otherwise)
- [ ] Icons from `lucide-react`, not mixed icon libraries
- [ ] Class merging uses `cn()`, not string concatenation
- [ ] External utility libs accessed through adapter modules (**except** Better Auth via `@/lib/auth-client`)
- [ ] No `date-fns`, `dayjs`, `axios`, `lodash`, etc. imported directly in `apps/` or component files
- [ ] Adapters export domain-specific function names, not raw library re-exports
- [ ] New components installed in `packages/ui/`, not `apps/web/`
- [ ] No redundant `lib/auth-http`-style module that only forwards `fetch` to Better Auth — use docs pattern instead
